illustrations, chapters compare the intelligence markers of cetaceans with those of birds, bats, and primates, asking how we might properly define intelligence in nonhumans. As all-encompassing and profound as the seas in which these deep cetacean cultures have evolved, Deep Thinkers is an awesome and inspiring journey into the fathoms—a reminder of what we gain through their close study, and of what we lose when the great minds of the sea disappear.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAnimal communication. 0aAnimal intelligence. 0aCetaceaxBehavior. 0aCetaceaxPsychology. 0aCognition in animals. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh  aaquatic, water, undersea, intelligent animals, dolphins, whales, porpoises, mammals, ocean, oceanography, ichthyology, earth, social structures, songs, singing, society, self recognition, sentience, sentient, cetacean, biology, biologist, science, scientific, scientist, academic, scholarly, research, brains, mind, mental, intelligence, cognition.1 aButti, Camilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarley, Heidi E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHof, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanik, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMann, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMann, Janet, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPatterson, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRead, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRendell, Luke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSayigh, Laela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhitehead, Hal, econtributor.